Developers expect `@Alternative` to win the injection point but leave other beans in the container for `Instance` lookup. The mental model is "priority ordering among all candidates" when the reality is "total removal of @DefaultBean beans when any non-default bean exists."

The ArC javadoc confirms: *"Default beans can optionally declare @Priority. Priority value is used for bean ordering and during typesafe resolution to disambiguate multiple matching default beans."* This `@DefaultBean @Priority` pattern is the correct way to have two platform-provided defaults with deterministic selection.

### Why this fix

`@DefaultBean @Priority` is architecturally correct — both beans are "defaults" that yield to consumer-provided beans. `@Alternative` implies the bean is an override, which is semantically wrong when both beans are platform infrastructure that should coexist.

### Alternatives considered

- **CDI qualifiers** (`@Named`, custom qualifier) — would work but forces callers to qualify injection points. Breaks the "just add to classpath" activation model.
- **Conditional activation** (`@IfBuildProperty`) — too rigid; the coexistence scenario is legitimate in deployments using both adapters.

**See also:** GE-20260601-fcf0d9 — two @DefaultBean beans for the same type give AmbiguousResolutionException, not Unsatisfied | GE-20260623-c651a1 — removing @Alternative from one bean in a multi-implementation chain silently changes resolution

LangChain4j 1.x: ChatLanguageModel renamed to ChatModel; chat() replaced by doChat() as extension point

## What changed

In LangChain4j 1.x, `ChatLanguageModel` was renamed to `ChatModel`. Code that compiled against 0.x fails immediately with `cannot find symbol: class ChatLanguageModel`.

The import path is now `dev.langchain4j.model.chat.ChatModel`.

## Extension point also changed

In 0.x, `ChatLanguageModel` had abstract methods that implementations overrode directly (`generate()`). In 1.x, **all** `ChatModel` methods are `default`. The single extension point is `doChat(ChatRequest)` — override it in anonymous classes or implementations. Lambda stubs fail because `ChatModel` is not a functional interface.

```java
// 0.x — lambda worked (was a functional interface)
ChatLanguageModel stub = messages -> Response.from(AiMessage.from("ok"));

// 1.x — must use anonymous class, override doChat
ChatModel stub = new ChatModel() {
    @Override
    public ChatResponse doChat(ChatRequest request) {
        return ChatResponse.builder().aiMessage(AiMessage.from("ok")).build();
    }
};
```

## Convenience entry points

`ChatModel` retains convenience defaults: `chat(String)` builds a `ChatRequest` from the string and calls `doChat()`. Callers invoking `llm.chat(prompt)` continue to work — only the implementation class and override point changed.

## Why non-obvious

The rename is not surfaced in compiler errors — `ChatLanguageModel` simply doesn't exist in 1.x, so the error looks like a missing dependency rather than a rename. Searching for `ChatLanguageModel` in the new codebase returns nothing. The migration guide exists but isn't the first place developers look when their code stops compiling.

QuarkusTestProfile.getEnabledAlternatives() replaces quarkus.arc.selected-alternatives — does not merge

## Symptom

A test using `@TestProfile` with `getEnabledAlternatives()` returning `Set.of(MyTestBean.class)` causes `@Alternative` beans selected via `quarkus.arc.selected-alternatives` in `application.properties` to be silently deactivated. For example, `MemoryPlanItemStore` stops being active and the application starts with `JpaPlanItemStore` instead — typically causing a startup failure (`HumanTaskRecoveryService` queries `WorkAdapterPlanItemEntity` which isn't mapped to Hibernate in the test context) or a wrong bean injection with no diagnostic pointing at the profile.

## Root Cause

`getEnabledAlternatives()` in `QuarkusTestProfile` **replaces** the effective set of selected alternatives for that profile — it does not ADD to the `quarkus.arc.selected-alternatives` value in `application.properties`. Any `@Alternative` bean that relies on the config property for activation is deactivated if not explicitly listed in `getEnabledAlternatives()`.

## Fix

**Option A:** Include ALL required `@Alternative` beans in `getEnabledAlternatives()` — not just the test-specific one:

```java
@Override
public Set<Class<?>> getEnabledAlternatives() {
    return Set.of(
        MyTestBean.class,
        MemoryPlanItemStore.class,
        MemorySubCaseGroupRepository.class,
        JpaLedgerEntryRepository.class
        // every @Alternative from application.properties goes here
    );
}
```

**Option B:** Replace the `@TestProfile` + `@Alternative` inner class with `@InjectMock` on the SPI interface. This avoids the profile entirely and leaves the standard `selected-alternatives` config intact:

```java
@QuarkusTest
class MyTest {
    @InjectMock MySpi spi;

@BeforeEach
    void setup() {
        when(spi.evaluate(any())).thenReturn(testResult);
    }
}
```

## Why This Is Non-Obvious

The name `getEnabledAlternatives()` implies additive behaviour — "enable these alternatives (in addition to the defaults)". The actual semantics are replacement — enabling these alternatives IS the complete set. The `application.properties` config is ignored in favour of the profile's set, with no log message indicating that previously-selected alternatives have been dropped.

**See also:** [GE-20260521-3ce7ca](GE-20260521-3ce7ca.md) — @Alternative @Priority(1) from external JAR needs exclude-types + selected-alternatives | [GE-20260429-a79d0e](GE-20260429-a79d0e.md) — @Alternative @Priority auto-activates within same module | [GE-20260519-12efe9](GE-20260519-12efe9.md) — QuarkusTestProfile.getEnabledAlternatives() scopes @Alternative to single @QuarkusTest class | [GE-20260531-70e07c](GE-20260531-70e07c.md) — Quarkus test-profile arc.exclude-types does not apply to production augmentation

casehub-qhorus MessageService methods using Panache static calls bypass InMemory store in @QuarkusTest

## Symptom

In a `@QuarkusTest` that relies on `InMemoryMessageStore` (from `casehub-qhorus-testing`), calling `messageService.findAllByCorrelationId(correlationId)` returns an empty list even though messages were dispatched to that correlationId moments before in the same test. The messages exist in the InMemory store but are invisible to this method.

## Context

`OversightGateService.fulfill()` calls `messageService.findAllByCorrelationId(gateId.toString())` to look up the original COMMAND message's Long ID (needed as `inReplyTo` for the RESPONSE dispatch). In `@QuarkusTest` with InMemory stores, this always returns empty — causing the service to log "no COMMAND message found" and fail open.

## Root Cause

`MessageService.findAllByCorrelationId()` is implemented with a Panache static call:

```java
public List<Message> findAllByCorrelationId(final String correlationId) {
    return Message.<Message> find("correlationId = ?1 ORDER BY id ASC", correlationId).list();
}
```

This bypasses the `MessageStore` interface entirely and queries Hibernate/H2 directly. The `InMemoryMessageStore` (the `@Alternative @Priority(1)` test bean) stores messages in a `ConcurrentHashMap` — it is never consulted by Panache static calls.

Most other `MessageService` methods inject and delegate to `MessageStore` — those work correctly with InMemory stores. Only the methods that use Panache static calls are affected.

## Fix

Wrap the problematic method with `@InjectSpy` in the test class and override only the bypassing method to scan the InMemory store:

```java
@InjectSpy
MessageService messageService;

@Inject
InMemoryMessageStore messageStore; // or inject the store interface directly

@BeforeEach
void mockFindAllByCorrelationId() {
    doAnswer(inv -> {
        String correlationId = inv.getArgument(0);
        return messageStore.findAll().stream()
            .filter(m -> correlationId.equals(m.correlationId))
            .sorted(Comparator.comparingLong(m -> m.id))
            .collect(Collectors.toList());
    }).when(messageService).findAllByCorrelationId(anyString());
}
```

All other `messageService` calls continue to use the real implementation; only `findAllByCorrelationId` is bridged to the InMemory store.

## Why This Is Non-Obvious

The `InMemoryMessageStore` gives the impression that all Qhorus data access is intercepted in tests. It isn't — only access that flows through the `MessageStore` interface is intercepted. Methods that call Panache directly bypass it silently: no error, just empty results. The real `InMemoryMessageStore` is injected correctly; it simply never receives the query.

**See also:** [GE-20260512-66d997](GE-20260512-66d997.md) — Panache static methods bypass CDI @Alternative stores (general pattern)

---

**Resolved in: casehub-qhorus 0.2-SNAPSHOT (2026-06-01, casehubio/qhorus#228)** — All four Panache-direct methods (`findByCorrelationId`, `findAllByCorrelationId`, `findResponseByCorrelationId`, `findDoneByCorrelationId`) now route through `messageStore.scan()`. `MessageQuery` gained `correlationId(String)` and `messageType(MessageType)` include filters; `MessageQueryJpql` and `InMemoryMessageStore.scan()` both apply them. The `@InjectSpy` workaround is no longer needed on fixed versions. The `invalidation_triggers` field predicted this fix exactly.

### Alternative — Mock MessageService + direct fanOut (ChannelBackend testing)

**Approach:** When testing a `ChannelBackend` implementation that calls `MessageService` read methods, mock `MessageService` entirely with `@InjectMock` and trigger the backend via `gateway.fanOut()` directly instead of going through `MessageService.dispatch()`.

**When to use:** Testing the `post()` logic of a `ChannelBackend` in isolation — verifying it calls the LLM, dispatches the right `MessageType`, and sets the correct `inReplyTo`. Does not test the full dispatch pipeline.

**Pros:** Avoids the store-seam issue entirely; tests the backend in isolation; fast (no full Qhorus transaction overhead).
**Cons/trade-offs:** Does not prove the backend integrates correctly with the full dispatch→fanOut→commitment lifecycle.

```java
@QuarkusTest
class MyChannelBackendTest {
    @Inject ChannelGateway gateway;
    @Inject MyChannelBackendFactory factory;

@InjectMock MessageService messageService;   // mock to control findByCorrelationId
    @InjectMock MyLlmService llm;               // mock to control LLM output

@Test
    void queryDispatchesResponse() {
        UUID channelId = UUID.randomUUID();
        String correlationId = UUID.randomUUID().toString();

// Stub the inReplyTo lookup
        Message stubQuery = new Message();
        stubQuery.id = 42L;
        when(messageService.findByCorrelationId(correlationId)).thenReturn(Optional.of(stubQuery));
        when(llm.review(any(), any(), any(), any(), any()))
            .thenReturn(new ReviewResult(false, "Looks good."));

// Register the backend
        factory.put(session);
        gateway.initChannel(channelId, new ChannelRef(channelId, "my-prefix/" + sessionId));

// Trigger via fanOut — bypasses MessageService.dispatch() entirely
        gateway.fanOut(channelId, "my-prefix/" + sessionId, new OutboundMessage(
            UUID.randomUUID(), "human:user", MessageType.QUERY, "Is this clear?",
            UUID.fromString(correlationId), null, ActorType.HUMAN));

// Verify the backend dispatched a RESPONSE
        ArgumentCaptor<MessageDispatch> captor = ArgumentCaptor.forClass(MessageDispatch.class);
        verify(messageService).dispatch(captor.capture());
        assertThat(captor.getValue().type()).isEqualTo(MessageType.RESPONSE);
        assertThat(captor.getValue().inReplyTo()).isEqualTo(42L);
    }
}
```

**See also:** [GE-20260608-5087c8](GE-20260608-5087c8.md) — @QuarkusTest @InjectSpy MessageService: COMMAND with correlationId does not trigger ChannelBackend.post()

Test Quarkus CDI SPI implementations with @Alternative static inner classes — Mockito cannot be injected as CDI beans

## Test Quarkus CDI SPI implementations with @Alternative static inner classes — Mockito cannot be injected as CDI beans

### What it achieves

Verifies that CDI SPI wiring works correctly in a `@QuarkusTest` context, with full control over what the test double records and returns.

### Context

Quarkus CDI resolves beans at augmentation time (build time). Mockito mocks and anonymous classes cannot be registered as CDI alternatives at test runtime — ARC doesn't know about them during augmentation. Attempting to inject a Mockito mock as a CDI alternative fails silently or selects the wrong bean.

### The technique

Define SPI test doubles as `@Alternative @ApplicationScoped` **static inner classes** within the test class. Use static fields to record invocations. Reset in `@BeforeEach`.

**Critical:** static inner classes do NOT auto-activate just because they are `@Alternative`. You must explicitly list them in `quarkus.arc.selected-alternatives` in the test profile using the outer class `$` inner class FQN:

```properties
# In the test profile section of application.properties:
%my-test-profile.quarkus.arc.selected-alternatives=\
  io.example.JpaRepository,\
  io.example.WorkerProvisionerTest$RecordingProvisioner
```

Note: `@Priority(N)` alone is NOT sufficient for inner class activation in Quarkus Arc — the explicit `selected-alternatives` entry is always required.

```java
@QuarkusTest
@TestProfile(WorkerProvisionerTest.Profile.class)
class WorkerProvisionerTest {

public static class Profile implements QuarkusTestProfile {
        @Override public String getConfigProfile() { return "my-test-profile"; }
    }

@Alternative @ApplicationScoped
    static class RecordingProvisioner implements WorkerProvisioner {
        static List<ProvisionContext> calls = new ArrayList<>();

@Override
        public Worker provision(ProvisionContext ctx) {
            calls.add(ctx);
            return Worker.noop();
        }
    }

@BeforeEach
    void reset() { RecordingProvisioner.calls.clear(); }

@Test
    void verifyProvisionerCalled() {
        // trigger work that should call the provisioner
        assertThat(RecordingProvisioner.calls).hasSize(1);
    }
}
```

### Why this is non-obvious

Mockito is the default testing reflex for Java. The CDI augmentation constraint isn't documented prominently — it only surfaces as a wrong-bean-injected failure or a silent no-invocation result. The static inner class pattern feels unusual but is the correct CDI-aware approach.

The additional non-obvious constraint: unlike top-level `@Alternative` classes in `src/test/java/`, static inner classes inside a `@QuarkusTest` class are indexed by Quarkus but are NOT automatically activated as alternatives — they still need explicit `selected-alternatives` registration. This contradicts the intuition that "if Quarkus can see it, it will use it." See GE-20260417-c59817 for the full `selected-alternatives` mechanism.

**Update 2026-05-13:** Verified on Quarkus 3.32.2 — `@Priority(1)` on the inner class alone does not activate it. Only `quarkus.arc.selected-alternatives` with the `OuterClass$InnerClass` FQN works reliably.

