Quarkus named persistence unit EntityManager injection uses io.quarkus.hibernate.orm.PersistenceUnit — not jakarta.persistence.PersistenceUnit

## What exists but isn't documented

When using multiple Hibernate ORM persistence units in Quarkus, injecting a specific PU's `EntityManager` requires a Quarkus-specific CDI qualifier — **not** the standard JPA annotation.

**Wrong** (standard JPA — doesn't work as a CDI qualifier):
```java
@PersistenceContext(unitName = "qhorus")
EntityManager em;
```

**Wrong** (another natural attempt):
```java
@Inject
@Named("qhorus")
EntityManager em;
```

**Correct** (Quarkus CDI qualifier):
```java
import io.quarkus.hibernate.orm.PersistenceUnit;

@Inject
@PersistenceUnit("qhorus")
EntityManager em;
```

## Context

Applies to any class that directly injects `EntityManager` when multiple Hibernate ORM persistence units are configured via `quarkus.hibernate-orm.<name>.*`. Panache-based stores (`PanacheEntityBase`, `PanacheRepositoryBase`) don't need this — they automatically route to the correct PU based on the `quarkus.hibernate-orm.<name>.packages` config covering the entity's package.

## Why non-obvious

The JPA specification defines `@PersistenceContext`/`@PersistenceUnit` for named PU injection. Quarkus replaces this mechanism with its own CDI qualifier `io.quarkus.hibernate.orm.PersistenceUnit`. The Quarkus multiple datasources documentation mentions named PUs but doesn't clearly state that CDI-style `@Inject + @PersistenceUnit` is the required pattern rather than the standard JPA annotations.

**See also:** GE-20260423-885412 — @PersistenceUnit is a standalone qualifier; adding @Inject breaks CDI resolution | GE-20260422-f86f42 — dual-PU setup when a library injects @Default EntityManager

**See also:** [GE-20260424-a29f1c](GE-20260424-a29f1c.md) — IntelliJ strips exactly this @PersistenceUnit qualifier silently; [GE-20260424-6b88a0](GE-20260424-6b88a0.md) — quarkus.ledger.datasource routes to named PU

**See also:** [GE-20260512-4d6f48](GE-20260512-4d6f48.md) — Panache entities cannot be scanned by two Quarkus persistence units simultaneously

Mutiny idiom for synchronous delegation: invoke(delegate::method).replaceWithVoid(), not call-then-return-voidItem

### Context

Writing a reactive wrapper that delegates to a synchronous implementation — e.g.
`InMemoryReactiveAgentRegistry` delegating to `InMemoryAgentRegistry`.

### Technique

Use `Uni.createFrom().item(x).invoke(delegate::method).replaceWithVoid()` instead of
calling `delegate.method()` synchronously and then returning `Uni.createFrom().voidItem()`.

```java
// ❌ Synchronous-then-wrap (bad template):
@Override
public Uni<Void> register(AgentDescriptor descriptor) {
    delegate.register(descriptor);          // synchronous call outside any Uni
    return Uni.createFrom().voidItem();
}

// ✅ Idiomatic Mutiny pipeline:
@Override
public Uni<Void> register(AgentDescriptor descriptor) {
    return Uni.createFrom().item(descriptor)
        .invoke(delegate::register)         // synchronous work inside the pipeline
        .replaceWithVoid();
}
```

### Why this is non-obvious

Both approaches are **functionally identical** for in-memory implementations with no I/O —
the synchronous call completes immediately in either case. The difference is invisible at
runtime for this use case.

The problem is the pattern it sets. When a future implementer adds real I/O to the delegate
and follows the `delegate.call(); return Uni.voidItem()` template, they silently place
blocking work **outside the reactive subscription**. This can happen on the event-loop thread
and block all other requests.

The `invoke()` pipeline keeps the work inside the Mutiny subscription chain where thread
dispatch (`@Blocking`, `.runSubscriptionOn(executor)`) can safely govern it.

**Rule of thumb:** in reactive interfaces, never call blocking-capable methods outside a
Uni/Multi pipeline. `invoke()` is the right seam for synchronous side-effects inside a
pipeline.

Synthesised delegation methods need explicit `public` when overriding interface methods

## Symptom

A code generator that synthesises delegation methods for interface implementations produces classes that fail to compile with: `attempting to assign weaker access privileges; was public`.

## Context

Any code generator (annotation processor, JavaParser-based, AST transformer) that synthesises concrete method bodies implementing an interface. The synthesised methods omit `public` because the source AST (the interface) doesn't have `public` on its method declarations — interface methods are implicitly public.

## Root cause

In Java, interface methods are implicitly `public`. When a code generator reads the interface's method signatures using a parser/reflection API, the `public` modifier is absent from the method node. Naively copying that signature into the implementing class produces a method with package-private access, which is a weaker access level than the interface contract — a compile error.

## Fix

When synthesising delegation methods that implement an interface, always add `public` explicitly:

```java
// Reading from source interface — method has no explicit 'public'
MethodDeclaration srcMethod = sourceInterface.getMethods().get(0);
// srcMethod.getModifiers() → [] (empty — implicitly public in interface)

// WRONG: copy modifiers directly
String methodSrc = srcMethod.getModifiers() + " " + srcMethod.getType() + " ...";
// → "void result(A a)" — package-private in the class, compile error

// CORRECT: always add public for interface implementations
String methodSrc = "public " + srcMethod.getType() + " " + srcMethod.getNameAsString() + ...;
```

In JavaParser, check the source type: if `sourceType instanceof ClassOrInterfaceDeclaration coid && coid.isInterface()`, add `public` modifier.

## Why this is non-obvious

When reading interface methods from source AST or reflection, the absence of `public` in the method node is technically correct — Java omits it. But this creates a trap for any code generator that copies method signatures: the correct behaviour in an interface context becomes incorrect in a class context. The `public` must be synthesised, not copied.

WorkItemService.delegate() must run strategy BEFORE clearing assigneeId or Hibernate auto-flush corrupts workload counts

## Symptom

A `WorkerSelectionStrategy` that counts active WorkItems per candidate (`countActive()`)
returns 0 for the delegating actor even though they have active items. This causes
least-loaded routing to incorrectly include the delegator as a candidate with low load.

## Context

In `WorkItemService.delegate()`, the flow is:
1. Retrieve WorkItem from store (Hibernate first-level cache)
2. Set `item.assigneeId = toAssigneeId` and `item.status = PENDING`
3. Call `assignmentService.assign(item, DELEGATED)` ← workload counted here
4. Call `workItemStore.put(item)` ← Hibernate flush

The strategy's `countActive()` queries the DB for `WHERE assigneeId = :delegator AND status IN (ASSIGNED, IN_PROGRESS, SUSPENDED)`.

## What was tried

Placing the strategy call AFTER `workItemStore.put()` — Hibernate flushes on `put()`,
updating `assigneeId` to null/toAssigneeId in the DB before the query runs. The delegator
appears to have zero active items.

## Root cause

Hibernate flushes dirty entities when `persistAndFlush()` is called (inside `put()`).
If `item.assigneeId` was already cleared before the strategy reads workload counts,
the DB reflects the new state — the delegator's item no longer appears as "assigned to them".
The strategy sees an inaccurate snapshot.

## Fix

Call the assignment strategy BEFORE mutating `item.assigneeId` or `item.status`:

```java
public WorkItem delegate(UUID id, String actorId, String toAssigneeId) {
    final WorkItem item = requireWorkItem(id);
    // ... validate state ...

// CORRECT: strategy fires first, with delegator still showing their full workload
    assignmentService.assign(item, AssignmentTrigger.DELEGATED);

// Then mutate state (strategy may have already set assigneeId)
    if (item.assigneeId == null || item.assigneeId.equals(actorId)) {
        item.assigneeId = toAssigneeId;
        item.status = WorkItemStatus.PENDING;
    }
    item.delegationChain = ...;
    item.delegationState = DelegationState.PENDING;

final WorkItem saved = workItemStore.put(item);
    // Audit uses saved.assigneeId (actual result, not toAssigneeId param)
    audit(saved.id, "DELEGATED", actorId, "to:" + saved.assigneeId);
    ...
}
```

Also: use `saved.assigneeId` (not `toAssigneeId`) in the audit record — when the
strategy overrides the requested target, the audit must reflect who actually got the item.

## Why this is non-obvious

The bug is invisible unless the delegating actor has active items AND the test checks
routing outcomes after delegation. Standard Hibernate flush-on-put semantics are
well understood, but the interaction with a query-in-the-same-transaction strategy
call is subtle. The test infrastructure creates items and delegates them in one transaction,
making the timing hard to observe without specifically testing "does the delegator's
active count affect routing?".

**See also:** GE-20260421-4a9364 — JpaWorkItemStore.scan() with assigneeId also matches candidateUsers LIKE; GE-20260415-a13ed7 — @Transactional JAX-RS method writes visible immediately within same transaction

Refactoring tests to extend an abstract base class silently removes implementation-specific test methods

## Refactoring tests to extend an abstract base class silently removes implementation-specific test methods

### Symptom

Test count drops unexpectedly (e.g. 92 → 62) after refactoring standalone test classes to extend an abstract contract base. No test failures — just fewer tests than before.

### Context

When refactoring `InMemoryChannelStoreTest` (standalone) into a class that extends `ChannelStoreContractTest` (abstract base), the implementer replaced the entire file with factory method implementations only. The implementation-specific tests that tested store-specific behaviour beyond the contract (e.g. `scan_bySemantic`, `countByChannel`, `clear_removesAll`) were simply omitted — there was no error, just fewer tests.

### What was tried

Replacing each test class body with only the abstract method implementations, assuming the abstract base's `@Test` methods would be inherited and provide equivalent coverage.

### Root cause

The abstract base only defines the minimum shared contract. Any test methods that covered behaviour specific to the implementation (methods not in the abstract interface, edge cases, extra query filters) must be explicitly carried over to the concrete class as supplemental `@Test` methods alongside the inherited ones.

### Fix

When refactoring to an abstract base pattern, the concrete class must:
1. Implement all abstract factory methods (delegation to the store)
2. Keep or migrate ALL existing test methods that are not covered by the abstract base
3. Verify the test count before and after — it should be ≥ the original count

The concrete class should look like:
```java
class InMemoryChannelStoreTest extends ChannelStoreContractTest {
    // Factory methods (required)
    @Override protected Channel put(Channel c) { return store.put(c); }
    // ... other abstract methods ...

// Supplemental tests (must NOT be removed)
    @Test void scan_bySemantic_returnsMatching() { ... }
    @Test void clear_removesAll() { ... }
}
```

### Why this is non-obvious

The refactoring "succeeds" silently — the build passes, all inherited tests pass, and there are no compilation errors. The only signal is a reduced test count, which is easy to miss if you're not watching the numbers. The instinct is to "simplify" the concrete class to just the delegation code.

CDI delegate pattern: reactive in-memory store wraps blocking store to share state across both interfaces in @QuarkusTest

## Problem solved

In `@QuarkusTest`, test setup uses `@BeforeEach channelStore.put(channel)` (blocking in-memory store) because reactive alternatives like `ReactiveChannelService.create()` require a Vert.x context unavailable on JUnit test threads. But reactive service code under test injects `ReactiveChannelStore` — a different interface backed by a different implementation. The blocking `put()` is invisible to the reactive service.

## Technique

Create a separate reactive delegate bean that injects the blocking in-memory store and wraps every method in `Uni.createFrom().item()`. Because both beans are CDI singletons, they share the same backing state:

```java
@Alternative
@Priority(1)
@ApplicationScoped
public class InMemoryReactiveChannelStore implements ReactiveChannelStore {

@Inject
    InMemoryChannelStore blocking; // CDI injects the @ApplicationScoped singleton

@Override
    public Uni<Channel> put(Channel channel) {
        return Uni.createFrom().item(() -> blocking.put(channel));
    }

@Override
    public Uni<Optional<Channel>> findByName(String name) {
        return Uni.createFrom().item(() -> blocking.findByName(name));
    }

@Override
    public Uni<List<Channel>> scan(ChannelQuery query) {
        return Uni.createFrom().item(() -> blocking.scan(query));
    }

@Override
    public Uni<Void> delete(UUID id) {
        return Uni.createFrom().voidItem().invoke(ignored -> blocking.delete(id));
    }
}
```

**Why this works:**
- `@BeforeEach channelStore.put(channel)` writes to `InMemoryChannelStore`
- CDI injects the same `InMemoryChannelStore` singleton into `InMemoryReactiveChannelStore.blocking`
- Reactive service code calls `ReactiveChannelStore.findByName()` → `InMemoryReactiveChannelStore` → delegates to `InMemoryChannelStore` → sees the test data
- `@AfterEach channelStore.clear()` clears `InMemoryChannelStore`, which automatically clears what the reactive view sees

**Key:** Make the `blocking` field package-private (no `private`) so `@BeforeEach` setup code in the same package can inject a specific instance for unit tests that don't use CDI:

```java
@Inject
InMemoryChannelStore blocking = new InMemoryChannelStore(); // CDI overwrites this
```

## Why this is non-obvious

