ChatModel.doChat(ChatRequest) is the override point for test doubles — not chat(ChatRequest)

## The technique

When implementing a test `ChatModel` without mocks (because `AiMessage`/`ChatResponse` have final methods), override `doChat(ChatRequest)` — not `chat(ChatRequest)`:

```java
ChatModel testModel = new ChatModel() {
    @Override
    public ChatResponse doChat(final ChatRequest request) {
        // inspect request, return appropriate response
        return ChatResponse.builder()
                .aiMessage(new AiMessage("{...json...}"))
                .build();
    }
};
```

`chat(ChatRequest)` is a **default method** in the `ChatModel` interface that calls `chat(ChatRequest, ChatRequestOptions)`, which then calls `doChat(ChatRequest)`. The chain applies listeners, merges request parameters, and fires `onRequest`/`onResponse` hooks. By overriding `doChat()`, the test skips the listener chain and returns directly.

`casehub-engine-api`'s `Agent.execute()` calls `model.chat(request)` which eventually reaches `doChat()`.

## Why this is non-obvious

`chat(ChatRequest)` and `chat(ChatRequest, ChatRequestOptions)` are the visible API methods that developers see in IDE autocompletion. `doChat(ChatRequest)` is buried as an implementation detail — a `default` method with a `throw new RuntimeException("Not implemented")` body that exists specifically as the override target. The JavaDoc doesn't prominently surface this as the intended extension point for test doubles.

**See also:** [GE-20260618-5008f5](../casehub-engine/GE-20260618-5008f5.md) — @Alternative @Priority(10) CDI test bean avoids Quarkus CDI restart (related CDI testing technique)

@Alternative on a CDI bean silently suppresses all @DefaultBean beans of the same type — they vanish from the container entirely

### Symptom

`Instance<ChatModel>` iteration returns only the `@Alternative` bean. The `@DefaultBean` ChatModel (registered by quarkus-langchain4j via `SyntheticBeanBuildItem.defaultBean()`) is completely absent from the container — not deprioritized, gone.

### Context

A platform module needed to provide a `ChatModel` adapter (`@Alternative @Priority(10)`) that wraps an `AgentProvider` as a `ChatModel`. The same deployment also has quarkus-langchain4j providing a raw `ChatModel` as `@DefaultBean`. A second bean uses `Instance<ChatModel>` to find the raw model — but after filtering out the adapter, nothing remains.

### What was tried (didn't work)

`@Alternative @Priority(10) @ApplicationScoped` on the adapter bean. Expected: both the adapter and the raw `@DefaultBean` ChatModel visible in `Instance<ChatModel>`, with `@Priority` disambiguating for direct injection. Actual: the raw `@DefaultBean` ChatModel vanishes entirely.

### Root cause

ArC's `@DefaultBean` semantics state: *"the bean will only be used if no other bean of this type is configured."* An `@Alternative` with `@Priority` counts as "another bean" — it suppresses the `@DefaultBean` entirely, removing it from the container. This is not priority ordering — it is total suppression.

### Fix

Use `@DefaultBean @Priority(10)` instead of `@Alternative @Priority(10)`.

```java
// WRONG — suppresses quarkus-langchain4j's @DefaultBean ChatModel
@Alternative
@Priority(10)
@ApplicationScoped
public class AgentProviderChatModel implements ChatModel { ... }

// RIGHT — coexists with other @DefaultBean ChatModel beans
@DefaultBean
@Priority(10)
@ApplicationScoped
public class AgentProviderChatModel implements ChatModel { ... }
```

Two `@DefaultBean` beans coexist — neither suppresses the other. `@Priority(10)` wins for direct `@Inject ChatModel` injection. `Instance<ChatModel>` sees both, enabling runtime filtering.

A consumer-provided non-`@DefaultBean` ChatModel properly overrides both defaults — the `@DefaultBean` suppression rule works as expected when a "real" bean is present.

### Why this is non-obvious

Developers expect `@Alternative` to win the injection point but leave other beans in the container for `Instance` lookup. The mental model is "priority ordering among all candidates" when the reality is "total removal of @DefaultBean beans when any non-default bean exists."

The ArC javadoc confirms: *"Default beans can optionally declare @Priority. Priority value is used for bean ordering and during typesafe resolution to disambiguate multiple matching default beans."* This `@DefaultBean @Priority` pattern is the correct way to have two platform-provided defaults with deterministic selection.

### Why this fix

`@DefaultBean @Priority` is architecturally correct — both beans are "defaults" that yield to consumer-provided beans. `@Alternative` implies the bean is an override, which is semantically wrong when both beans are platform infrastructure that should coexist.

### Alternatives considered

- **CDI qualifiers** (`@Named`, custom qualifier) — would work but forces callers to qualify injection points. Breaks the "just add to classpath" activation model.
- **Conditional activation** (`@IfBuildProperty`) — too rigid; the coexistence scenario is legitimate in deployments using both adapters.

**See also:** GE-20260601-fcf0d9 — two @DefaultBean beans for the same type give AmbiguousResolutionException, not Unsatisfied | GE-20260623-c651a1 — removing @Alternative from one bean in a multi-implementation chain silently changes resolution

Agent.build() bakes ChatModel once — @InjectMock on ChatModelProvider is silently ignored after first augment()

## Symptom

`@InjectMock LifeOpenClawChatModelProvider openClaw` is set up in `@BeforeEach` for an `AppointmentCycleCaseHub` integration test. The stub returns a specific `ChatModel`. But when `agent.execute()` is called, the ChatModel from a completely different test class (or the real provider) is used instead — the mock is silently ignored.

## Root Cause

`AgentBuilder.build()` calls `chatModelProvider.get()` exactly **once** and stores the result in the `Agent` object:

```java
ChatModel resolvedModel = model;
if (resolvedModel == null && chatModelProvider != null) {
    resolvedModel = chatModelProvider.get();  // called ONCE at build time
}
return new Agent(... resolvedModel ...);
```

When `AppointmentCycleCaseHub.getDefinition()` uses a double-checked lock:

```java
private volatile CaseDefinition augmentedDefinition;

@Override
public CaseDefinition getDefinition() {
    if (augmentedDefinition == null) {
        synchronized (this) {
            if (augmentedDefinition == null) {
                augmentedDefinition = augment(super.getDefinition());
            }
        }
    }
    return augmentedDefinition;
}
```

`augment()` calls `Agent.build()` which calls `provider.get()` — only on the **first** `getDefinition()` call per JVM lifetime. The baked `ChatModel` is stored permanently in `augmentedDefinition`.

Quarkus's `@InjectMock` reset between test methods restores the CDI delegate of the provider bean — but the `Agent` already holds a direct reference to the `ChatModel` returned by the first `get()`. No subsequent `@InjectMock` setup can change what `agent.execute()` uses.

## Fix

Use a test-only `@Alternative @Priority(10) @ApplicationScoped` CDI bean (registered in `quarkus.arc.selected-alternatives` in test config) that returns a request-aware `ChatModel`. Whichever test class triggers `getDefinition()` first bakes the request-aware model — all subsequent test classes benefit.

```java
@Alternative
@Priority(10)
@ApplicationScoped
public class TestLifeOpenClawChatModelProvider extends LifeOpenClawChatModelProvider {
    @Override
    public ChatModel get() {
        return new ChatModel() {
            @Override
            public ChatResponse doChat(ChatRequest request) {
                // request-aware: examine message text to route responses
                boolean decline = extractUserText(request).toLowerCase().contains("unavailable");
                return decline ? declineResponse() : successResponse();
            }
        };
    }
}
```

**Never use `@InjectMock`** on `ChatModelProvider` implementations when the provider's `get()` is called during lazy-init of an `@ApplicationScoped` singleton. The baked result cannot be replaced after the first call.

## Why this is non-obvious

The CDI proxy for `LifeOpenClawChatModelProvider` IS replaced by `@InjectMock` — every call to `openClaw.type()` or `openClaw.get()` would go through the mock if called directly. But `Agent` stores the `ChatModel` value returned by `get()`, not a reference to the provider. Once stored, the CDI proxy is bypassed entirely.

Nothing in the `@InjectMock` documentation, LangChain4J API, or Quarkus test framework warns that `ChatModel` references baked into eager-building beans cannot be replaced.

Uni.createFrom().emitter() is wrong for one-shot callback bridging — use completionStage() + CompletableFuture.orTimeout()

## Symptom

Wrapping a streaming callback API into `Uni<T>` using `Uni.createFrom().emitter()` appears to work — but the Uni has no built-in timeout, the risk of calling `emitter.complete()` in both `onCompleteResponse` and `onError` exists, and `emitter()` semantics are for push streams, not one-shot results.

## Context

When bridging a callback-based async API (e.g. `StreamingChatModel.chat(request, handler)` from LangChain4j) into a Mutiny `Uni<T>`, `emitter()` looks like the natural choice. But it has three problems for one-shot use: (1) no built-in timeout — a hung provider hangs the Uni indefinitely, (2) it is designed for push streams where `emit()` may be called many times, (3) both `onCompleteResponse` and `onError` callbacks could call `emitter.complete()` by mistake, causing IllegalStateException.

## Root Cause

`Uni.createFrom().emitter()` is a push-stream primitive. For a one-shot async result (exactly one completion or error), the correct primitive is `CompletableFuture` — which has timeout support via `orTimeout()`, clear single-completion semantics, and maps cleanly to Mutiny via `Uni.createFrom().completionStage()`.

## Fix

```java
CompletableFuture<Optional<T>> future = new CompletableFuture<>();
llm.chat(request, new StreamingChatResponseHandler() {
    @Override
    public void onCompleteResponse(ChatResponse response) {
        future.complete(parseOrEmpty(response.aiMessage().text()));
    }
    @Override
    public void onError(Throwable error) {
        future.completeExceptionally(error);  // not future.complete(empty) — let onFailure handle it
    }
});
return Uni.createFrom().completionStage(
        future.orTimeout(TIMEOUT_SECONDS, TimeUnit.SECONDS))
    .onFailure().recoverWithItem(e -> {
        log.warn("Streaming LLM failed (" + e.getMessage() + "), falling back");
        return Optional.empty();
    });
```

`onError` calls `completeExceptionally` — the `onFailure().recoverWithItem()` in Mutiny handles both timeout and LLM errors uniformly, and the fallback is explicit at the Mutiny level.

## Why This Is Non-Obvious

`emitter()` is the most prominent `Uni.createFrom()` variant for async work and the name sounds right for a callback-based API. The problems (no timeout, push-stream semantics, double-complete risk) only surface under failure conditions — in the happy path, `emitter()` and `completionStage()` behave identically.

LangChain4j 1.x: implementing both ChatModel and StreamingChatModel requires explicit overrides for all four shared default methods

### Symptom
Java compile error when a class implements both `ChatModel` and `StreamingChatModel`:
the compiler reports ambiguous default methods.

### Context
When building a LangChain4j adapter that needs to satisfy both `ChatModel` (blocking)
and `StreamingChatModel` (streaming) injection points in a single CDI bean.

### What was tried
Implementing both interfaces and overriding only the extension-point methods —
`doChat(ChatRequest) → ChatResponse` and `doChat(ChatRequest, StreamingChatResponseHandler)`.
These compile fine in isolation.

### Root cause
Both `ChatModel` and `StreamingChatModel` declare four identical default method signatures:
- `listeners()` → `List<ChatModelListener>`
- `defaultRequestParameters()` → `ChatRequestParameters`
- `provider()` → `ModelProvider`
- `supportedCapabilities()` → `Set<Capability>`

Java's diamond rule requires a class implementing both interfaces to explicitly override
every method where both declare a default. All four must be overridden — not just the
extension points.

### Fix
Override all four in the implementing class:

```java
@Override public ModelProvider provider() { return ModelProvider.ANTHROPIC; }

@Override public Set<Capability> supportedCapabilities() { return Set.of(); }

@Override public ChatRequestParameters defaultRequestParameters() {
    return DefaultChatRequestParameters.EMPTY;
}

@Override public List<ChatModelListener> listeners() {
    return List.of();  // or return injected CDI listeners
}
```

### Why this is non-obvious
`ChatModel` and `StreamingChatModel` are designed as complementary interfaces —
implementing both in one class is a natural choice when building a single adapter for
both injection points. The shared default methods aren't mentioned in LangChain4j
documentation. The compiler error only appears when implementing both simultaneously;
either interface alone compiles cleanly with only the `doChat()` extension point overridden.

