**See also:** [GE-20260518-069f64](GE-20260518-069f64.md) — calling @Transactional method via this inside Mutiny lambda silently bypasses CDI proxy

Use Instance<T> for optional CDI injection — resolves gracefully to null when no bean exists

## Context

A library module needs to use a CDI bean (e.g. `EmbeddingModel`) that may or may not be present in the consuming application's classpath. Direct `@Inject EmbeddingModel` would fail with `UnsatisfiedResolutionException` at CDI startup when no provider is configured.

## Technique

Inject `Instance<T>` instead of `T` directly. `Instance<T>` is always satisfiable — CDI never fails to inject it. Call `instance.isResolvable()` at use time to check whether a bean actually exists:

```java
@Inject
public EmbeddingSkillMatcher(final Instance<EmbeddingModel> modelInstance) {
    this.model = modelInstance.isResolvable() ? modelInstance.get() : null;
}
```

At call time, check and degrade gracefully:

```java
public double score(SkillProfile profile, SelectionContext ctx) {
    if (model == null) {
        LOG.warn("No EmbeddingModel available — returning -1.0");
        return -1.0;
    }
    // ... call model
}
```

For unit tests, inject a concrete `EmbeddingModel` directly via a package-private test constructor — no `Instance<>` wrapper needed:

```java
// Test constructor — bypasses CDI
EmbeddingSkillMatcher(final EmbeddingModel model) {
    this.model = model;
}
```

## Why this is non-obvious

Most developers either:
1. Use direct `@Inject T` (fails at boot when bean is absent)
2. Use `@Inject @Default T` with a no-op default bean (pollutes CDI context)
3. Wrap everything in `@IfBuildProperty` conditions (ties optional behaviour to build time)

`Instance<T>` solves this purely at runtime, with no build-time conditions and no extra beans. The pattern is documented in the CDI spec but rarely seen in practice because the common case is non-optional injection.

### Why this fix

`Instance<T>` is the CDI-native solution for optional dependencies. Alternatives (no-op default beans, build-time conditions) add complexity and make testing harder. `Instance<T>` keeps the code clean and the library usable in both AI-enabled and AI-disabled contexts.

**See also:** GE-20260422-f922f3 — quarkus-langchain4j-core stalls @QuarkusTest augmentation when no model provider configured

LangChain4j 1.x: ChatLanguageModel renamed to ChatModel; chat() replaced by doChat() as extension point

## What changed

In LangChain4j 1.x, `ChatLanguageModel` was renamed to `ChatModel`. Code that compiled against 0.x fails immediately with `cannot find symbol: class ChatLanguageModel`.

The import path is now `dev.langchain4j.model.chat.ChatModel`.

## Extension point also changed

In 0.x, `ChatLanguageModel` had abstract methods that implementations overrode directly (`generate()`). In 1.x, **all** `ChatModel` methods are `default`. The single extension point is `doChat(ChatRequest)` — override it in anonymous classes or implementations. Lambda stubs fail because `ChatModel` is not a functional interface.

```java
// 0.x — lambda worked (was a functional interface)
ChatLanguageModel stub = messages -> Response.from(AiMessage.from("ok"));

// 1.x — must use anonymous class, override doChat
ChatModel stub = new ChatModel() {
    @Override
    public ChatResponse doChat(ChatRequest request) {
        return ChatResponse.builder().aiMessage(AiMessage.from("ok")).build();
    }
};
```

## Convenience entry points

`ChatModel` retains convenience defaults: `chat(String)` builds a `ChatRequest` from the string and calls `doChat()`. Callers invoking `llm.chat(prompt)` continue to work — only the implementation class and override point changed.

## Why non-obvious

The rename is not surfaced in compiler errors — `ChatLanguageModel` simply doesn't exist in 1.x, so the error looks like a missing dependency rather than a rename. Searching for `ChatLanguageModel` in the new codebase returns nothing. The migration guide exists but isn't the first place developers look when their code stops compiling.

Two @Startup @ApplicationScoped Quarkus beans have no guaranteed initialization order — @PostConstruct side effects are unreliable across beans

### Symptom

Bean A's `@PostConstruct` sets a shared global (e.g. `Path.setDefaultParser()`). Bean B's `@PostConstruct` calls code that depends on that global. Works in some environments, fails silently or intermittently in others because the order in which Quarkus initialises `@Startup` beans is not defined.

### Context

Any Quarkus application with two or more `@Startup @ApplicationScoped` beans where one bean's `@PostConstruct` produces a side effect (global state, static field, registry population) that another bean's `@PostConstruct` consumes.

### Root cause

CDI specifies no initialization ordering between two `@Startup @ApplicationScoped` beans. The order is implementation-defined and can vary between test and production environments. `@Startup` only guarantees that all such beans initialise before the first non-startup request — not relative to each other.

### Fix

Each `@Startup` bean reads `@ConfigProperty` directly rather than depending on another bean's `@PostConstruct` side effect. Pass the config value explicitly to helpers that need it.

```java
// BAD — depends on PathParserConfigurator.@PostConstruct having set the default parser
Path parser = Path.getDefaultParser(); // may be null or default at this point

// GOOD — read the same config key directly; CDI injects @ConfigProperty fields
// before @PostConstruct, regardless of @Startup ordering between beans
@ConfigProperty(name = "casehub.platform.path.separator", defaultValue = "/")
String pathSeparator;

@PostConstruct
void load() {
    PathParser parser = PathParser.of(pathSeparator); // explicit, no cross-bean dependency
    // ...
}
```

`@ConfigProperty` fields are always injected before `@PostConstruct` runs — that guarantee is per-bean, not cross-bean, and is reliable.

### Why this is non-obvious

`@Startup` implies "at startup" — developers assume multiple `@Startup` beans initialise in a predictable order (e.g. dependency graph or declaration order). The CDI spec guarantee is only that they initialise before the first non-startup request, not relative to each other. The failure is intermittent and environment-dependent, making it hard to reproduce reliably.

