Config-driven CDI strategy selection: Instance<T>.select(NamedLiteral.of(name)).get() in @PostConstruct

## What it is

Select a CDI bean by name at startup from a config property using `Instance<T>` and `NamedLiteral`. Zero framework code beyond `@Named` on each implementation.

## When to use it

When you have multiple implementations of an interface, want to select one via config (`application.properties`), and want the selection to happen once at startup with fast-fail if the name is wrong.

## The pattern

```java
// Interface
public interface KiteStrategy {
    Point2d retreatTarget(Unit unit, List<Unit> enemies);
}

// Implementations
@ApplicationScoped @Named("direct")
public class DirectKiteStrategy implements KiteStrategy { ... }

@ApplicationScoped @Named("terrain-aware")
public class TerrainAwareKiteStrategy implements KiteStrategy { ... }

// Selector bean
@ApplicationScoped
public class TacticsController {

@Inject
    @ConfigProperty(name = "quarkmind.tactics.kite.strategy", defaultValue = "direct")
    String kiteStrategyName;

@Inject Instance<KiteStrategy> kiteStrategies;

private KiteStrategy kiteStrategy;

@PostConstruct
    void init() {
        kiteStrategy = kiteStrategies.select(NamedLiteral.of(kiteStrategyName)).get();
    }
}
```

Config:
```properties
quarkmind.tactics.kite.strategy=terrain-aware
```

## Why this is non-obvious

Most developers reach for a factory class, a switch statement, or `@Alternative` + `@Priority`. The `Instance<T>.select(NamedLiteral.of(name))` idiom is in the CDI spec but rarely shown in examples. Key benefits:
- **Fast fail at startup** — `get()` throws `UnsatisfiedResolutionException` immediately if the name doesn't match any `@Named` bean, not silently at call time
- **Zero factory boilerplate** — CDI discovers all implementations automatically; adding a new strategy is just a new `@Named` class
- **Future-extensible** — a `@Named("lua") LuaStrategy` implementation can be added without touching the selector

`NamedLiteral.of(name)` is from `jakarta.enterprise.inject.literal.NamedLiteral` (CDI 4.x / Quarkus 3.x).

**See also:** GE-20260421-566d3d (self-registering strategy registry via @Any Instance<T> + name() for O(1) lookup)

@Alternative on a CDI bean silently suppresses all @DefaultBean beans of the same type — they vanish from the container entirely

### Symptom

`Instance<ChatModel>` iteration returns only the `@Alternative` bean. The `@DefaultBean` ChatModel (registered by quarkus-langchain4j via `SyntheticBeanBuildItem.defaultBean()`) is completely absent from the container — not deprioritized, gone.

### Context

A platform module needed to provide a `ChatModel` adapter (`@Alternative @Priority(10)`) that wraps an `AgentProvider` as a `ChatModel`. The same deployment also has quarkus-langchain4j providing a raw `ChatModel` as `@DefaultBean`. A second bean uses `Instance<ChatModel>` to find the raw model — but after filtering out the adapter, nothing remains.

### What was tried (didn't work)

`@Alternative @Priority(10) @ApplicationScoped` on the adapter bean. Expected: both the adapter and the raw `@DefaultBean` ChatModel visible in `Instance<ChatModel>`, with `@Priority` disambiguating for direct injection. Actual: the raw `@DefaultBean` ChatModel vanishes entirely.

### Root cause

ArC's `@DefaultBean` semantics state: *"the bean will only be used if no other bean of this type is configured."* An `@Alternative` with `@Priority` counts as "another bean" — it suppresses the `@DefaultBean` entirely, removing it from the container. This is not priority ordering — it is total suppression.

### Fix

Use `@DefaultBean @Priority(10)` instead of `@Alternative @Priority(10)`.

```java
// WRONG — suppresses quarkus-langchain4j's @DefaultBean ChatModel
@Alternative
@Priority(10)
@ApplicationScoped
public class AgentProviderChatModel implements ChatModel { ... }

// RIGHT — coexists with other @DefaultBean ChatModel beans
@DefaultBean
@Priority(10)
@ApplicationScoped
public class AgentProviderChatModel implements ChatModel { ... }
```

Two `@DefaultBean` beans coexist — neither suppresses the other. `@Priority(10)` wins for direct `@Inject ChatModel` injection. `Instance<ChatModel>` sees both, enabling runtime filtering.

A consumer-provided non-`@DefaultBean` ChatModel properly overrides both defaults — the `@DefaultBean` suppression rule works as expected when a "real" bean is present.

### Why this is non-obvious

Developers expect `@Alternative` to win the injection point but leave other beans in the container for `Instance` lookup. The mental model is "priority ordering among all candidates" when the reality is "total removal of @DefaultBean beans when any non-default bean exists."

The ArC javadoc confirms: *"Default beans can optionally declare @Priority. Priority value is used for bean ordering and during typesafe resolution to disambiguate multiple matching default beans."* This `@DefaultBean @Priority` pattern is the correct way to have two platform-provided defaults with deterministic selection.

### Why this fix

`@DefaultBean @Priority` is architecturally correct — both beans are "defaults" that yield to consumer-provided beans. `@Alternative` implies the bean is an override, which is semantically wrong when both beans are platform infrastructure that should coexist.

### Alternatives considered

- **CDI qualifiers** (`@Named`, custom qualifier) — would work but forces callers to qualify injection points. Breaks the "just add to classpath" activation model.
- **Conditional activation** (`@IfBuildProperty`) — too rigid; the coexistence scenario is legitimate in deployments using both adapters.

**See also:** GE-20260601-fcf0d9 — two @DefaultBean beans for the same type give AmbiguousResolutionException, not Unsatisfied | GE-20260623-c651a1 — removing @Alternative from one bean in a multi-implementation chain silently changes resolution

