Remove JAX-RS coupling from @ApplicationScoped service beans using inner static domain exception classes

## Context

A `@Transactional @ApplicationScoped` service bean throws `ClientErrorException` or
`WebApplicationException` to signal not-found or conflict conditions to the calling JAX-RS
resource. This imports `jakarta.ws.rs.*` into the service layer — a layer violation:
services should not know about HTTP semantics.

The obvious alternatives all have problems:

- **`ClientErrorException` in service**: works at runtime but imports JAX-RS into service layer
- **Move validation to resource**: breaks `@Transactional` atomicity if validation and
  mutation must be atomic (TOCTOU: another request changes the entity between the check and
  the service call)
- **Checked exception hierarchy**: requires callers to catch or declare; awkward with
  `@Transactional` which only auto-rolls back on `RuntimeException`
- **`ExceptionMapper<MyException>`**: correct for cross-module use but adds infrastructure
  overhead for a module-local pattern

## Technique

Define lightweight inner static `RuntimeException` subclasses on the service itself.
They carry no HTTP knowledge. The JAX-RS resource catches them and maps to builder-based
responses — keeping HTTP concerns in the HTTP layer.

```java
@ApplicationScoped
public class TrialActivationService {

public static class TrialNotFoundException extends RuntimeException {
        private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;
        public TrialNotFoundException(UUID id) { super("Trial not found: " + id); }
    }

public static class TrialNotInPlanningStatusException extends RuntimeException {
        private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;
        public TrialNotInPlanningStatusException(TrialStatus status) {
            super("Trial status is " + status + ", expected PLANNING");
        }
    }

@Transactional
    Map<String, Object> markActive(UUID trialId) {
        ClinicalTrial trial = ClinicalTrial.findById(trialId);
        if (trial == null) throw new TrialNotFoundException(trialId);
        if (trial.status != TrialStatus.PLANNING) throw new TrialNotInPlanningStatusException(trial.status);
        // ... validation and mutation are atomic
    }
}

// In the JAX-RS resource:
public Response activate(@PathParam("id") UUID id) {
    try {
        trialActivationService.activate(id);
        return Response.noContent().build();
    } catch (TrialActivationService.TrialNotFoundException e) {
        return Response.status(Response.Status.NOT_FOUND).build();
    } catch (TrialActivationService.TrialNotInPlanningStatusException e) {
        return Response.status(Response.Status.CONFLICT).build();
    }
}
```

`RuntimeException` ensures `@Transactional` auto-rolls back on error. Inner static
placement means the exception is co-located with its thrower — one file to read for both
semantics and error conditions. The resource catch block is the single place where HTTP
status codes are decided.

## Why this is non-obvious

The instinct when a service needs to signal error conditions to HTTP callers is to reach
for `ClientErrorException` (it's in the JAX-RS API, it exists for exactly this) or to
move validation up to the resource layer. The inner static class pattern is not in any
JAX-RS guide because it's a layering discipline choice, not a JAX-RS feature.

The key insight is that the service's error taxonomy (`TrialNotFound`, `WrongStatus`)
is domain knowledge, not HTTP knowledge. The HTTP mapping (`NOT_FOUND`, `CONFLICT`) is the
resource's responsibility. Separating the two — domain exception on the service, HTTP
mapping on the resource — preserves both layer boundaries and `@Transactional` atomicity
without any infrastructure overhead.

java.net.http.HttpClient.send() does NOT throw for 4xx/5xx — returns HttpResponse with statusCode()

## Symptom

HTTP GET responses with 4xx or 5xx status codes are processed as if they were successful. No exception is thrown. Error body bytes (HTML error pages, JSON error responses) are silently treated as valid response data.

## Context

Polling arbitrary URLs with `java.net.http.HttpClient` and using the response body as data. The code has a `try/catch (IOException e)` block around the `send()` call expecting to catch failed requests.

## Root Cause

`HttpClient.send()` signature:
```java
public abstract <T> HttpResponse<T> send(HttpRequest request, HttpResponse.BodyHandler<T> handler)
    throws IOException, InterruptedException;
```

`IOException` is thrown only for **connection-level failures**: DNS resolution failure, TCP connection errors, connection timeout, SSL handshake failure. A 4xx or 5xx HTTP response is a **successful HTTP exchange** from the network perspective — the server received the request and returned a response. `send()` returns the response with `response.statusCode()` set to the error code; no exception is thrown.

## Fix

Always check the status code explicitly after `send()`:

```java
HttpResponse<byte[]> response = httpClient.send(request, BodyHandlers.ofByteArray());
if (response.statusCode() < 200 || response.statusCode() >= 300) {
    throw new IOException("HTTP " + response.statusCode() + " for " + url);
}
// 2xx: use response.body() safely
byte[] data = response.body();
```

## Why This Is Non-Obvious

`java.net.http.HttpClient` differs from many older HTTP client libraries (Apache HttpClient, OkHttp) that DO throw exceptions for 4xx/5xx by default. Developers migrating from those libraries or relying on exception-based error handling will miss error responses entirely. The consequence — error body bytes silently processed as valid data — can corrupt downstream pipelines with no log entry or observable failure.

RESTEasy Reactive: return CompletionStage<Response> to chain async engine calls without @Blocking

### Context
A JAX-RS endpoint needs to call an async engine method that returns `CompletionStage<T>` (e.g. `CaseHub.startCase()` returning `CompletionStage<UUID>`), transform the result, and return an HTTP response — without blocking a Vert.x event thread.

### What developers normally do
Annotate the method with `@Blocking` and call `.toCompletableFuture().get()` — or use `Uni<Response>` and unwrap manually. Both either block a thread or require Mutiny familiarity.

### Technique
Return `CompletionStage<Response>` directly from the JAX-RS method. RESTEasy Reactive natively suspends the HTTP request on the event loop and resumes when the stage completes — no `@Blocking`, no `.get()`, no thread held:

```java
@POST
@Path("/cases/researcher")
public CompletionStage<Response> startResearcher() {
    if (engine.isUnsatisfied()) {
        return CompletableFuture.completedFuture(
            Response.status(Response.Status.SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE)
                .entity(Map.of("error", "engine not available"))
                .build());
    }
    return engine.get()
        .startCase()
        .thenApply(caseId -> Response.accepted(new CaseStartedResponse(caseId)).build());
}
```

For the absent-engine 503 path, `CompletableFuture.completedFuture(...)` returns an already-resolved stage — RESTEasy Reactive handles it the same way, completing synchronously.

### Why this is non-obvious
`CompletionStage<Response>` as a JAX-RS return type is not prominent in Quarkus docs — examples focus on `Uni<Response>` (Mutiny) or blocking endpoints. The pattern works because RESTEasy Reactive checks the return type at augmentation time and generates a non-blocking handler for `CompletionStage`. No annotation, no framework import — just the JDK type.

